PostgreSQL replication setup:

  Primary (write + read)

      |

    WAL (Write-Ahead Log) stream

      |          |

  Replica 1   Replica 2  (read-only)

  (sync)      (async)

  Node.js connection:

  const writePool = new Pool({ host: 'primary' });

  const readPool  = new Pool({ host: 'replica-lb' });

  // Route automatically

  const read  = (sql) => readPool.query(sql);

  const write = (sql) => writePool.query(sql);

Outbox Pattern (most reliable):

BEGIN TRANSACTION;

  INSERT INTO orders (id, user_id, status) VALUES (...);

  INSERT INTO outbox (event_type, payload, status)

         VALUES ('order.created', '{ ... }', 'PENDING');

COMMIT;

-- Background job: poll outbox, publish, mark PUBLISHED

-- Ensures: event published IF AND ONLY IF order saved

-- Handles: service crash between save and publish

Problem: trace a request across 10 microservices

  Request arrives at API Gateway

    -> User Service -> Order Service -> Payment Service

    -> Inventory Service -> Notification Service

  Where is the bottleneck? Which service is slow?

OpenTelemetry (OTLP standard):

  Trace: end-to-end request tree

  Span:  one unit of work in trace

  Context propagation: trace_id passed in headers

  Headers: traceparent: 00-{trace_id}-{parent_span_id}-01

// Node.js OpenTelemetry

const tracer = opentelemetry.trace.getTracer('order-service');

const span = tracer.startSpan('processOrder');

span.setAttribute('order.id', orderId);

try {

  await processOrder(orderId);

  span.setStatus({ code: SpanStatusCode.OK });

} catch (err) {

  span.recordException(err);

} finally {

  span.end();

}

Jaeger UI shows: timeline of all spans, their duration

  -> Identify bottleneck instantly

States:

  CLOSED -> normal operation, track failures

  OPEN   -> reject all requests, return fallback

  HALF-OPEN -> allow test requests

  CLOSED:  failures < threshold -> stay CLOSED

           failures >= threshold -> OPEN

  OPEN:    all requests fail fast (no downstream call)

           after timeout -> HALF-OPEN

  HALF-OPEN: limited requests go through

              success -> CLOSED

              failure -> OPEN

// Node.js with opossum

const CircuitBreaker = require('opossum');

const breaker = new CircuitBreaker(callPaymentService, {

  timeout: 3000,

  errorThresholdPercentage: 50,

  resetTimeout: 30000,

  volumeThreshold: 10  // min requests before tripping

});

breaker.fallback(() => ({ status: 'payment-unavailable' }));

breaker.on('open',     () => logger.warn('CB OPEN'));

breaker.on('halfOpen', () => logger.info('CB HALF-OPEN'));

breaker.on('close',    () => logger.info('CB CLOSED'));

const result = await breaker.fire(orderData);
